Node.Notes: The pp's in vs. 2, 3, and 4 refer back to v. 1, stating some way in which the proverbs are useful.

Righteousness, justice, and fairness are most likely three additional qualities (besides prudence) that can be developed by one who practices the discipline of learning the proverbs. It is less likely that they are three aspects of prudence (an appositional reading).

While "a proverb and a parable" and "the sayings of the wise and their riddles" probably refer to a similar group of referents, they are not in apposition (an implied second "to understand" is involved, so that we have two parallel lists, with the second being similar, but more intensified.
The poetic imagery of "garland of grace " and "chains for the neck" represents the teaching given by parents as enhancing the character of the child just as adornment enhances physical beauty.

Node.Notes: This expression may mean either “be one of us when we cast lots to divide the proceeds,” or more likely figuratively “join us, associate your fate with ours."
Possessor of wings is poetic expression for birds like "winged creature" or 飞禽.
(SYNTAX) While IO is a possible interpretation for "you," I am taking this as "I would have made you know my thoughts" with the causative verb (so V-O2-O instead of V-O-IO).
